<TEXT>
sten andersson smiled at the television in his 
hotel suite when it carried the news that ended months of secret 
meetings and lastminute quibbles over words in two languages not 
his own 
the swedish foreign minister guided the diplomacy culminating in 
the us agreement to talk to the plo which secretary of state 
george p shultz announced wednesday night 
swedens effort to bring the united states and the palestine 
liberation organization together began on a trip andersson made to 
the middle east in march during that visit he saw the palestinian 
uprising now a year old against israeli rule in the occupied west 
bank and gaza strip 
i met with about 100 boys shot by israeli soldiers some of 
them paralyzed for life he told reporters thursday 
the 64yearold swedish diplomat went to jordan after israel and 
talks with two plo leaders convinced him they wanted a separate 
palestinian state rather than the destruction of israel palestinians 
had preached for decades 
egyptians saudi arabians and envoys from several european 
nations were involved in negotiations that followed andersson said 
he met with vernon a walters washingtons ambassador to the united 
nations and hinted to the journalists of contacts with shultz 
he said sweden acted as a postman delivering messages but 
added i confess we have written some of the letters too 
eugene makhlouf plo delegate to stockholm said the swedes did 
most of the diplomatic maneuvering they worked very hard until we 
achieved this result he said just after the shultz announcement 
andersson described his role to a few reporters early thursday 
morning and at a crowded news conference later he told the news 
conference he approached american jews not israelis because he did 
not want the israeli government to know about his activities in 
advance 
the most crucial event was the meeting with the jewish 
personalities from the united states attended by khalid elhassan 
of the plo a fortnight before plo chairman yasser arafat came 
to stockholm andersson said 
rita hauser a prominent member of the republican party led the 
american jewish delegation at the secret meeting elhassan is a 
leading figure in the plo and a confidant of arafat 
after the meeting the foreign minister said he wrote a document 
expressing the agreements reached and both sides agreed to sign it 
the document was not made public until last week when arafat 
visited stockholm to meet with ms hauser and other american jews 
most of the meeting with arafat dealt with strategy for 
persuading the us government to deal with the plo 
anderssons last maneuvers were performed wednesday afternoon 
when he settled arguments over which words in english and arabic the 
united states would accept in arafats announcement that he 
renounced terrorism and accepted israels right to exist 
on tuesday us officials had said a speech by arafat to the 
un general assembly in geneva did not meet american conditions for 
contacts with the plo 
that speech and his statement wednesday seemed much the same but 
andersson said arafats remarks at the news conference in english 
cleared up questions of language that had disturbed the americans 
he said all the ideas expressed wednesday were in arafats speech 
in arabic a day earlier but were split up and in different 
words 
arabs have a different way of making speeches than americans the 
swedish diplomat observed they use a lot of words a lot of words 
always cause confusion misunderstanding if he arafat changes 
the words the americans say whats going on here 
arafat said in the speech for instance that he condemned 
terrorism and at the news conference that he renounced it 
makhlouf said one word covers for both concepts in arabic the 
plo representative added that another element contributed to the 
delay in a favorable response from washington they didnt believe 
their ears yesterday tuesday they needed to hear it again 
andersson whose diplomatic involvement with the arabisraeli 
conflict covers 25 years said he felt the us decision was an 
important step in breaking the middle east stalemate 
the beginning of peace is always dialogue but it has a long 
way to go he said 
