<TEXT>
the agriculture department has resolved that 
the new year will bring an end to a fiveyear rulemaking snag 
involving food safety and the processing of oldfashioned country 
ham 
the deadline for ham producers to comply with new federal 
regulations was supposed to be dec 31 but it has been pushed back 
to the final day of 1989 the deadline once was dec 31 1987 and 
before that it was dec 31 1986 there also was one on aug 6 1985 
now the departments food safety and inspection service says it 
will stick to a deadline of dec 31 1989 or whenever the agency 
finally approves the new rules spokeswoman irene goins said 
thursday 
the lengthy rulemaking procedure involves those hams often seen 
on grocery shelves in cloth bags or hanging from rafters in country 
stores they must be scrubbed to remove mold and then soaked or 
boiled a couple of times to reduce the salt content 
theyre the kind of hams for which someone had to invent redeye 
gravy and in some parts of the country grits 
as the usda defines them theyre uncooked cured dried 
smoked or unsmoked pork products made from solid meat 
typically country or drycured hams are treated with salt and 
then put in a smokehouse to cure and age a total process that can 
take months or even years 
most hams sold in supermarkets are wetcured quickly in brine 
solutions and cooked before sale to consumers 
in march 1983 the usda proposed rules intended to help prevent 
trichinosis a disease caused by microscopic parasitic worms or 
trichinae that can occur in improperly cooked pork the proposed 
rules were directed at readytoeat pork products and drycured 
country hams 
shortly after the original proposal was adopted feb 6 1985 the 
agency learned that some federally inspected ham producers were 
using oldfashioned methods that didnt meet the new usda 
requirements and were ordered to show by aug 6 1985 that their 
curing procedures were safe 
the country ham industry protested so the usda allowed more 
time one compelling reason for the extensions of time for 
compliance was that no trichina problems had been associated with 
the drycured hams 
these traditional processing methods have been permitted 
because they are decadesold methods believed to be effective in 
destroying trichinae says ronald j prucha acting administrator 
of the usda agency 
we are researching the safety of traditional trichina control 
methods and developing a proposed rule for issuance in early 1989 
he said after we receive public comments on that proposal we 
will develop new regulations 
but just in case the usdas rulemaking machine is slower than 
officials hope the compliance deadline was extended another full 
year 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a 17 percent increase in the amount of raw 
sugar that can be imported from 39 foreign countries in 1989 has 
been announced by the agriculture department 
deputy secretary peter meyers said thursday that next years 
quota was set at about 124 million short tons of 2000 pounds each 
up from about 106 million tons in calendar 1988 
in metric tons which have about 2205 pounds each the 1989 
quota will be almost 113 million tons metric units were used to 
establish next years quota to meet the terms of a new us tariff 
system which will take effect jan 1 
the dominican republic led the list with a 1989 allocation of 
185328 metric tons followed by the philippines 166374 and 
brazil 152685 
reduced production because of this years drought and rising 
demand were the main reasons for boosting the quota so sharply 
officials said 
