the united states and greece today ended their 
12th round of talks on us military bases in the mediterranean 
nation without resolving important differences in the way of 
extending an agreement that expires tuesday state department 
officials said 
once the fiveyear leases for four bases and about 20 additional 
communications facilities expire the united states has 17 months to 
leave one official said the next round of talks on extending the 
agreement is scheduled for january said the officials all of whom 
requested anonymity 
important differences remain but the negotiations are not at an 
impasse said one 
one major obstacle is a greek demand that the united states close 
its most visible base the hellenikon air force base in suburban 
athens the base has been an irritant to nationalist and leftist 
groups opposed to the us presence in their country 
talks between the sides broke off in september after greece 
announced it would shut down hellenikon once the lease expires 
about 1400 american servicemen 200 civilian employees and 700 
greeks work at the base which was established in the 1940s 
negotiations resumed oct 3 after secretary of state george 
shultz met foreign minister carolos popoulias in washington 
since the 1950s the united states has operated four bases in 
greece in addition to hellenikon there is a navy communications 
base at nea makri near athens a navy installation at souda bay on 
the island of crete and an air force communications base at gournes 
also on crete 
the united states gives greece more than 430 million a year in 
military credits in exchange for the bases 
the government of socialist premier andreas papandreou has been 
under heavy pressure to remove the bases and the pressure is likely 
to increase during the campaign for june elections in greece 
