<TEXT>
a new immigration policy taking effect 
today in the lower rio grande valley will prevent thousands of latin 
american aliens seeking asylum in the united states from getting 
jobs and discourage them from traveling 
advocates for the aliens said the measure will sharply limit the 
number of people granted asylum and cause overcrowding that could 
overwhelm area social services 
omer g sewell harlingen district director for the immigration 
and naturalization service said the new procedure which is also 
being followed in miami and los angeles will make it tougher to 
file frivolous applications for political asylum 
were going to provide almost instant service here in the rio 
grande valley and give them answers here and give them answers 
quickly sewell said 
under the new policy asylum applications will be processed 
within 30 days and applicants cannot work while awaiting a 
decision sewell said 
aliens must also present their asylum applications at their point 
of entry in the united states on a given appointment date a new 
procedure that does not actually prohibit immigrants from leaving 
the area but makes travel unlikely 
previously applications could take several months to process 
aliens were allowed to travel to their us destinations and present 
their asylum applications there and they were generally allowed to 
work in the meantime 
but officials here and in such popular destinations as miami and 
los angeles say they are overwhelmed by the steadily increasing tide 
of applicants 
about 2000 applicants arrive at the harlingen office each week 
compared to a total of 405 for all of 1987 according to ins 
records south texas is the closest and most popular crossing point 
for undocumented aliens from central america 
nearly 30000 people primarily central americans have applied 
for asylum with the ins in harlingen since may 30 
