<TEXT>
france has been hit with its worst flu epidemic in 
20 years and by christmas one in five people will have suffered 
from high fever aching bones stuffy nose and other unpleasant flu 
symptoms doctors say 
the flu has hit harder and earlier than ever before said dr 
jeanmarie cohen head of frances regional groups for influenza 
observation 
cohen a general practitioner said one in three patients he 
treats have la grippe 
the epidemic is currently making its way south from northern 
france where it surfaced two weeks ago to the riviera where it is 
expected to peak during the holiday season 
more than 2 million people have been struck so far with this 
years variety which doctors attribute to the ah1n1 virus it is 
affecting mostly young adults and schoolage children 
the ah1n1 virus caused a major outbreak of flu in the late 
1940s so people over 40 are likely to be immune to it said karin 
esteves of the division of communicable diseases at the world health 
organization in geneva 
cohen said the virus first appeared during the summer in britain 
but did not reach epidemic proportions czechoslovakia was hard hit 
in early fall and sweden is now in the grip of the flu 
the ah1n1 virus also has turned up in canada and the united 
states with cases reported in arizona michigan maryland texas 
south dakota and hawaii he said 
in the french city of nantes on the atlantic coast about 30 
percent of schoolage children have been bedridden with the flu and 
in some scattered towns around france schools have been closed 
some doctors say recent transit strikes can be blamed for the 
flus rapid spread in the greater paris region 
many of my patients have walked miles in the cold and rain to 
get to work said dr joseph danon an ear nose and throat 
specialist and when they do catch buses or subways theyre 
crammed in like sardines an ideal way to spread germs 
cohen said it was virtually impossible to know why the flu struck 
so early this year especially since the weather in november was 
relatively mild 
in 1968 more than 30000 people died throughout france during a 
flu epidemic that lasted three weeks 
cohen was more optimistic for this years epidemic because a 
vaccination against the virus has been on the market since early 
oct with 12 percent of the population vaccinated it is expected to 
reduce incidence of the flu by 20 percent 
though doctors say the flu does not rank among the serious 
illnesses it does cost the french economy billions of dollars 
in 1985 workers missed 16 million days of work because of flu 
costing the french economy 15 billion many companies have begun 
vaccinating employees free of charge or for a nominal sum 
french pharmaceutical companies however did not produce enough 
vaccine to meet the demand and many pharmacies are sold out 
