<DOCNO> AP881216-0155 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a pipe crack found in the cooling system of a 
reactor at the savannah river nuclear weapons plant is a type of 
defect that has cropped up previously and does not represent new 
safety problems a department of energy spokesman said friday 
engineers at the weapons production facility near aiken sc 
have determined that the crack apparently resulted from heat due to 
welding work on the pipe doe spokesman gary pitchford said 
the washington post reported friday that the crack at the plants 
l reactor appeared to be either a flaw or stressinduced defect in 
the stainless steel pipe metal itself 
an official whom the newspaper did not identify said the problem 
was a potential showstopper that could seriously delay 
restarting the three reactors at the savannah river plant and 
possibly require the l reactor to be shut down permanently 
pitchford however said were now highly confident that what 
were seeing here is rather classical cracking intergranular 
stresscorrosion cracking which we have seen rather frequently in 
sensitized metal near where welding has been done 
it is a type of crack that we have seen before and does not in 
our view represent a new phenomenon we do not believe that the 
cracking we have seen represents a major safety concern or a new 
safety problem said the spokesman speaking by telephone from 
does savannah river office 
he added the implication is we need to make improvements and 
changes in our inservice inspection program but it is not a new 
type of cracking or representative of some new safety issue that we 
have not encountered before 
all three reactors at savannah river known as the k l and p 
reactors have been shut down due to maintenance and safety 
concerns 
the reactors are the nations only sources of tritium a 
radioactive isotope of hydrogen used to boost the explosive power of 
nuclear warheads because tritium decays at a rate of 55 percent a 
year it needs to be replenished regularly 
doe is seeking to restart by this summer the k reactor which is 
almost identical in design but older than the l reactor 
pitchford noted that cracks are not infrequently found in areas 
associated with welds its caused by what they call the 
heataffected zone of the metal the metal becomes sensitized in 
the parlance of the metallurgists 
sections of pipe are removed and replaced if a crack is found 
penetrating more than 50 percent of the pipe walls thickness or 
covering more than 20 percent of the pipes circumference 
as part of a regular inspection program pitchford said a 
crack was identified that met those criteria and a section of pipe 
was removed from the l reactor in october 1987 the program called 
for inspection of that pipe after removal that was done in march 
1988 
they found cracks in an unexpected location not associated 
with the original weld which caused the pipe to be removed but 
associated with a structural support welded to the outside of the 
pipe there were a series of cracks on the interior surface of the 
pipe in the heataffected zone where that structural support had 
been welded pitchford said 
the crack at the focus of particular concern was found during 
continued examination of the pipe using ultrasonic testing and 
other methods he said 
</TEXT>
