<TEXT>
a federal appeals court friday upheld a 
government decision allowing continued importation of a nuclear 
power plant fuel from south africa despite antiapartheid sanctions 
enacted by congress 
a split threejudge panel of the us circuit court of appeals 
here ruled that the petitioners lacked legal standing to challenge 
the nuclear regulatory commissions decision to allow continued 
importation of uranium hexafluoride from south africa 
the nrcs 1987 decision was challenged by seven members of 
congress four private organizations and two individuals including 
an unemployed uranium miner and an antiapartheid activist 
the petitioners had contended that the nrc failed to enforce the 
antiapartheid sanctions passed by congress in 1986 that forbid 
continued importation of south african uranium and uranium oxide 
the nrc had decided that the sanction law did not ban uranium 
hexafluoride a gas that is used to power nuclear reactors 
circuit judge laurence silberman wrote for the court but judge 
milton pollack filed a concurring opinion to express his uneasiness 
over whether legal standing should be the basis of the ruling 
judge ruth ginsburg who dissented on the standing question and 
pollack said they would uphold the nrc decision on the ground the 
agency properly interpreted the antiapartheid statute as allowing 
continued importation of the radioactive chemical 
ginsburg contended that the antiapartheid activist henry isaacs 
and transafrica inc a group that opposes white minority rule in 
south africa had standing in the case 
the congressmen who challenged the nrc decision were reps 
ronald v dellums dcalif mervyn m dymally dcalif william h 
gray iii dpa edward j markey dmass charles b rangel 
dny bill richardson dnm and howard wolpe dmich 
</TEXT>
