<TEXT>
a new immigration policy to sort out and 
deport immigrants filing unfounded political asylum claims before 
they travel farther into the united states began friday in the 
southern tip of texas 
the brownsville area is the main entry for central americans who 
cross the border illegally and claim political asylum and the new 
policy is expected to concentrate more displaced wouldbe immigrants 
in the lower rio grande valley 
it requires the 2000 asylum applicants each week present their 
cases in the area instead of waiting to apply until they reach 
their final destinations brownsville is about 30 miles south of 
harlingen 
very few of the immigrants intend to stay in impoverished 
southern texas where unemployment ranges from 12 percent to 50 
percent and many people live in rural slums that lack running water 
to deal with the workload from the new policy the immigration 
and naturalization service sent six additional adjudicators to 
harlingen to work 10 hours a day six days a week interviewing 
applicants it will send 20 more after jan 1 officials said 
the procedure applies to all nationalities but was designed to 
relieve the backlog of asylum applicants in places such as los 
angeles with 30000 pending cases and miami with a backlog of 
50000 said rick kenney an ins spokesman in washington 
similar procedures have taken effect in those two cities which 
are also congregating points 
in the lower rio grande valley refugee shelters have been filled 
to capacity for months many immigrants end up sleeping outdoors or 
in dilapidated immigrant motels 
ins harlingen district director jerry sewell said he hopes fewer 
people will come once word reaches central america that the agency 
is cracking down on asylum 
the ins turned people away friday in harlingen after limiting the 
number of asylum applicants to 200 for the day the ins has promised 
to provide decisions on the cases within 30 days and applicants 
were instructed to return jan 16 
files will be sent to washington for advisory opinions on each 
case 
ins officials said travel outside the area probably will be too 
expensive for most applicants who must return for their decisions 
or face deportation those denied asylum will be asked to leave the 
country within 30 days but may appeal through an immigration court 
ins officials maintain that most applicants are ineligible for 
asylum because they merely want to better themselves economically 
asylum generally is granted for political reasons 
previously when applicants applied at their destination cities 
some would wait more than a year for a decision because of the 
backlog cases taking longer than 60 days require the ins to provide 
work authorization which many received those in the faster process 
in harlingen however will not be allowed to work officials said 
in san francisco a federal judge issued a ruling this week that 
could affect the new ins policy if it is extended to other 
jurisdictions us district judge charles legge ruled that work 
permits must be given to aliens throughout their appeal of an asylum 
decision a process that can take several years 
legge ordered the ins to provide work permits to a group of farm 
workers from central america during the period in which their 
applications for asylum have been denied and a deportation hearing 
has not yet been scheduled 
refugee advocates contend that keeping the immigrants in southern 
texas while they await asylum decisions will only increase the 
misery and concentration of central americans in the area 
i think the people are going to be more visible said ninfa 
krueger with the border association for refugees from central 
america which provides legal advocacy and social services 
theres a concern already that we dont have the means to take 
care of them 
the policy is meant to scare people enough to make them stop 
coming but i think theyre more scared of the war and theyll keep 
coming ms krueger said 
antonio a 27yearold nicaraguan who illegally crossed the rio 
grande on inner tubes tuesday with a group of 25 immigrants waited 
outside the ins office friday 
i dont know where im going to go he said while looking for 
someone who understood enough english to help him fill out his 
application 
antonio who asked that his last name not be used in order to 
protect his family in managua said he has a relative in miami his 
intended destination where he could stay 
but i dont have the money to travel there and then come back 
here he said in spanish theres no place to go 
i think at first we may see a slightly higher number of aliens 
in the area but that will soon taper off as soon as word gets back 
to central america that harlingen is no longer providing a free 
ride said virginia kice an ins spokeswoman in harlingen 
</TEXT>
