a former chairman of the board of trustees of 
catholic university testified friday that the facultys academic 
freedoms were never clearly spelled out and therefore are not 
binding on the administration 
the board never defined academic freedom said cardinal 
joseph bernardin unless they approved a statement it is not 
binding said bernardin currently archbishop of chicago 
court papers revealed that in july 1968 the board of trustees 
adopted a statement ensuring academic freedom at the university 
lawyers for the rev charles e curran are seeking to prove that 
when catholic university revoked his right to teach theology 
university officials violated his academic freedom 
the nonjury trial included the testimony of two of the churchs 
highest officials in the country 
curran 54 is an ordained priest whose disagreement with church 
teachings on homosexuality birth control and other positions were 
pubished in his book faithful dissent afterward vatican 
officials revoked currans canonical mission to teach catholic 
theology 
cardinal james a hickey archibishop of washington and 
chancellor of the university thursday testified that the church had 
the authority to decide when an ordained priest no longer spoke for 
the church 
when the vatican revoked his priviledges curran was suspended by 
hickey 
catholic university was founded in 1885 as one of a few 
pontifical universities directly governed by the church 
bernardin testified the university risked severing its 
relationship with the church if it had not suspended curran 
if we were to directly defy the holy see the school risked 
having its charter revoked he said 
monsignor frederick mcmanus a catholic university canon law 
professor and the principal author of the canonical statutes said 
hickey played an honorific role as chancellor of the school and 
did not have the authority to decide who should or should not teach 
there 
currans lawyers arguing the case before superior court judge 
frederick h weisberg were trying to refute hickeys testimony on 
thursday that he as a representative of the vatican had the right 
to suspend curran 
curran sued the university after it revoked his right to teach 
theology on the grounds that his writings were at odds with the 
church curran had refused an offer to teach ethics outside of the 
universitys religious department he had taught at the school for 
22 years 
hickey archbishop of washington said he merely was enforcing 
the highest order of the church to suspend curran after the vatican 
revoked his right to teach roman catholic theology 
the university claims curran must obey the revocation of his 
mission to teach however curran counters that he never had such a 
mission and his contract is the same as other tenured professors at 
the university 
currans attorney paul saunders is seeking to prove that curran 
had no knowledge of his canonical mission and that hickeys 
suspension of curran was not sanctioned by canon law 
following his 1987 suspension curran served as a visiting 
professor at cornell he now has a oneyear appointment at the 
university of california los angeles 
