<TEXT>
in the midst of the enthusing over soviet leader 
mikhail s gorbachev and the remarkable reforms he has launched in 
the soviet union a pbs special wednesday reminds that all is not 
rosy on the other side of the iron curtain 
the title of the documentary czechoslovakia the long wait for 
spring refers to the prague spring of 1968 when reforms 
introduced by premier alexander dubcek raised hopes for new freedom 
after 20 years of hardline communism 
a few months later those hopes were crushed under the treads of 
invading soviet tanks today little evidence remains in 
czechoslovakia of the prague spring which ironically soviet 
citizens seem to be enjoying under gorbachevs policy of 
glasnost 
the documentary crams a lot of historical economic and 
sociopolitical information into one hour but also gives the 
country a human face 
viewers are taken on a whirlwind tour of the country from 
prague just as modern and beautiful as many other european cities 
at least on the surface to the grimy ironsmelting plants that seem 
to have been lifted from another era 
indeed the factories represent czechoslovakias biggest problem 
economic dependence on the soviet union to support an outdated 
heavy manufacturing industry czechoslovakia has little access to 
other markets except for its pilsner beer urquell which is 
exported to the west 
in addition czechoslovakia is one of the most polluted countries 
in europe with its reliance on cheap brown coal for heating and 
manufacturing 
there are interviews with dissidents who hold little hope of soon 
seeing the kind of reforms that gorbachev has introduced in the 
soviet union 
you have to have a gorbachev and in czechoslovakia so far no 
one like that has appeared says zdenek mlynar a member of the 
dubcek government who was interviewed in vienna where he lives in 
