wholesale prices that were flat in october 
after three months of fairly large increases are on the rise again 
but not at a dangerously inflationary pace according to economists 
with the labor departments producer price index figures for 
november due out today the consensus among private analysts was 
that wholesale prices rose a modest 03 percent last month 
inflationary fears exceed inflationary reality at the present 
time said donald ratajczak director of economic forecasting at 
georgia state university in atlanta 
any increase higher than 03 percent would aggravate inflation 
fears triggered by reports earlier this week that factories mines 
and power plants operated at a nineyear high of 842 percent of 
their capacity in october with industrial production up another half 
of a percentage point in november 
wholesale price inflation had slowed to zero in october as food 
prices that had been rising at an annual rate of 8 percent because 
of the summer drought decreased 
stable food prices or even another slight decline after seasonal 
adjustments showed up in november in private surveys as large hog 
slaughters continued to put downward pressure on pork prices 
beef prices were up sharply as were costs for vegetables as they 
became seasonally scarce but those factors were built into the 
seasonal adjustments that the government uses 
ratajczak said the big propellants of the november price 
increases were a firming in oil prices even prior to the 
establishment of new production quotas last month by the 
organization of petroleum exporting countries 
he said his own survey showed wholesale gasoline prices rising 2 
percent in november and home heat oil spurting up by 6 percent 
however natural gas prices stabilized after surging by nearly 5 
percent in october 
