european foreign ministers will refine 
next week their retaliatory plans if a trade war breaks out over a 
scheduled ban on hormonetreated meat from the united states 
officials said friday 
the ministers of the european economic community will discuss the 
dispute monday at a regularly scheduled meeting in brussels 
according to a spokeswoman for the 12nation trading bloc 
the community wants to ban for health reasons all meat from 
animals treated with growth hormones late last year it agreed to 
delay implementation of the prohibition until jan 1 
an estimated 170 million of us meat exports would be affected 
by the ban 
the united states has threatened to take retaliatory action if 
the prohibiton is imposed by slapping duties on a variety of 
products imported from the trading bloc the united states argues 
that the use of certain hormones to fatten animals a common 
practice among american farmers is not a health risk 
the eec has in turn promised to retaliate if any extra duties 
are imposed on its products 
a spokeswoman for the trading bloc who requested anonymity said 
the eec has drawn up a draft plan that would single out for 
retaliation four american products natural honey unshelled nuts 
dried fruit and canned corn exported to the community 
she did not specify what sort of restrictions would be placed on 
those products only that such action would depend on the us 
response other products could also be added to the list she said 
discussions were continuing to try to resolve the dispute 
officials from both sides also were expected to discuss the issue 
tuesday when they gather in geneva for a meeting of the general 
agreement on tariffs and trade the 96nation world trade 
organization 
