<TEXT>
the bull market for platinum looked to be about as close to a 
sure thing as commodities speculators were likely to find supplies 
were down consumption was up and demand was expected to outstrip 
production for years to come 
then wham the bottom fell out thursday on sketchy news about 
an experimental device for controlling auto pollution sending 
investors scrambling for cover 
market analysts proclaimed a catastrophe and went looking for 
silver linings 
they found some and it didnt take long by friday morning some 
were saying the market had overreacted to ford motor cos 
announcement of a platinumfree catalytic converter at least one 
analyst richard levine of elders futures inc said the sharp 
decline in the metals value from 600 to about 520 an ounce on 
the cash market represented a very good buying opportunity 
what happened 
the best place to start is a 24page review of the platinum 
market published nov 15 by londonbased johnson matthey plc the 
worlds largest platinum refiner 
in its report johnson matthey predicted a supply shortfall for 
platinum for the next five years including a record 465000ounce 
shortfall in 1988 
platinum is an essential element in todays automobile 
pollutioncontrol systems the metal in conjunction with certain 
other metals acts as a catalyst in chemical reactions that convert 
harmful exhaust pollutants into harmless carbon dioxide and water 
this process occurs inside metal boxes called catalytic converters 
that have been required since 1975 on all cars sold in the united 
states 
johnson matthey said it expected the use of platinum in catalytic 
converters in 1988 to account for nearly 75 percent of platinum 
demand in north america and for more than a third of world demand 
for the metal 
and the refiner said new pollution standards in europe would 
contribute to a steady increase in global platinum demand for the 
next six years 
all this amounted to an extremely bullish outlook for platinum 
prices investor dollars streamed into the platinum market pushing 
the metals value up from 480 an ounce in late september to 620 an 
ounce early this month on the new york mercantile exchange 
on wednesday night ford chairman donald peterson announced in a 
speech in pittsburgh that ford was ready to test a catalytic 
converter that did not use platinum on thursday morning platinum 
prices collapsed 
then the facts began to filter in the ford device was only 
experimental and would be tested only on 40000 to 50000 cars in 
california global demand for platinum for catalytic converters 
would likely remain strong at least over the next year or two 
despite the new converter physical supplies of platinum for 
nearterm delivery were still very tight 
and in a rather startling development johnson matthey issued a 
statement saying it had collaborated with ford in the development of 
the new converter and that it had taken the device into account in 
preparing its november platinummarket review 
in the short to medium term we dont believe this development 
is going to have any effect on platinum supplydemand fundamentals 
and we feel platinums longterm supplydemand outlook is not at all 
bad said jack robson one of the authors of johnson mattheys 
november report in a telephone interview from london 
some market analysts were outraged by johnson mattheys failure 
to disclose its ford connections in its november supplydemand 
report one called it unconscionable 
but the market seemed reassured by the refiners statement 
platinums price stabilized friday at about 520 an ounce on the 
cash market 
i would say there still is tremendous physical demand for 
platinum and there will be for the foreseeable future said 
analyst levine my view is that 500 platinum too cheap and 600 
is probably more reflective of the current supplydemand 
fundamentals 
</TEXT>
