<TEXT>
a delaware judge on friday invalidated 
pillsbury cos poison pill takeover defense setting up an 
expected appeal by pillsbury in its attempts to thwart a grand 
metropolitan plcs 549 billion hostile buyout bid 
retired justice william duffy of the court of chancery in 
wilmington del also issued a preliminary injunction blocking 
pillsburys plan to spin off its miamibased burger king corp 
another key element of pillsburys takeover defense 
earlier friday a minnesota state court judge also temporarily 
blocked the spinoff in a separate action requested by dissident 
pillsbury shareholders but withheld a ruling on the poison pill 
pending duffys decision 
however hennepin county dstrict judge thomas carey indicated he 
expected to side with the delaware courts ruling 
pillsbury a food and restaurant company based in minneapolis and 
incorporated in delaware had planned the burger king spinoff in an 
attempt to thwart grand met the british real estate liquor and 
gambling conglomerate 
duffy ruled on grand mets request to invalidate the poison pill 
so that it could go ahead with its 63ashare hostile tender offer 
the pill is considered pillsburys cornerstone defense against a 
takeover but an appeal would at least temporarily block grand met 
from buying the company 
stopping the poison pill was considered critical to grand mets 
tender offer because the defense would greatly increase the number 
of shares grand met would have to acquire making a buyout 
prohibitively expensive 
in the burger king transaction pillsbury planned to spin the 
fast food restaurant chain off into a new publicly traded company 
owned by pillsburys present shareholders 
the shareholders also would receive a special dividend payment 
and would retaing their stake in pillsbury 
in addition to grand met the proposed spinoff has been 
criticized by a number of burger king franchise holders on the 
grounds that the huge new debt needed to finance the special 
dividend would hinder the operations of the newly independent burger 
king 
in the minnesota case shareholders had filed a class action suit 
to compel pillsbury to negotiate with grand met a british 
conglomerate which launched a 60pershare tender offer on oct 4 
grand met sweetened its bid on monday to 63 a share or 55 
billion but pillsbury immediately rejected it as inadequate 
the shareholders said the plan threatened to block grand met from 
acquiring pillsbury pillsbury has said the spinoff would create a 
huge tax liability for grand met in the event of a takeover 
the record date of the spinoff was set for monday 
carey said the temporary enjoinment of the burger king spinoff 
causes insignificant harm to pillsbury and preserves the 
status quo 
careys ruling also denied the shareholders request to compel 
pillsbury to meet and bargain in good faith with grand met 
